    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-12-22T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-12-22T10:00:00-05:00" n="525"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d525">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">841d.01/228: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_WJG1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Winant</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-12-22T16:00:00+01:00"
                            >December 22, 1943—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>8893. Personal and secret to the Secretary.</p>
                <p>Your 8004, December 18, Department’s 7184, November 13,<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d525fn1">Neither printed herein. The subject of these telegrams was
                        the desire of the United States for British concurrence in a proposed
                        request to Ireland for the use of naval and air facilities if needed during
                        the war. According to <persName corresp="#p_HC1">Hull</persName> (vol. <hi
                            rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 1357), the British reaction was unfavorable
                        to the American proposal.</note> was held by the Embassy until my return and
                    because of the absence of both <persName corresp="#p_EA1">Eden</persName> and
                    the Prime Minister. I explained the British position on this issue to the
                    President in Cairo,<note n="2" xml:id="d525fn2">According to the Log, <hi
                            rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_298">pp. 298</ref>, <ref
                            target="#pg_299">299</ref>, <ref target="#pg_656">656</ref>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_WJG1">Winant</persName> conferred with <persName
                            corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName> at Cairo on November 25, November
                        26, and December 3, 1943.</note> having taken the matter up at great length
                    with the Prime Minister on my journey out there with him.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d525fn3">See <persName corresp="#p_WJG1">Winant</persName>’s
                        telegram of November 8, 1943, to <persName corresp="#p_RFD1"
                            >Roosevelt</persName>, <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_73"
                            >p. 73</ref>.</note> I understood the President would talk with the
                    Prime Minister on this subject but do not know the results of their
                    discussion.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WJG1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Winant</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
